{"parse":{"title":"Conjunct consonant","pageid":58447333,"revid":858933054,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:182px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_Kya_(Ka-Ya)_conjunct_consonant.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Brahmi_Kya_%28Ka-Ya%29_conjunct_consonant.jpg/180px-Brahmi_Kya_%28Ka-Ya%29_conjunct_consonant.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"201\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e7/Brahmi_Kya_%28Ka-Ya%29_conjunct_consonant.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"242\" data-file-height=\"270\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_Kya_(Ka-Ya)_conjunct_consonant.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>\"Kya\" (Ka+Ya) conjunct consonant in the <a href=\"/wiki/Brahmi_script\" title=\"Brahmi script\">Brahmi script</a>, consisting in the vertical assembly of consonants \"Ka\" <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_k.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi k.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/12px-Brahmi_k.svg.png\" width=\"12\" height=\"12\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/18px-Brahmi_k.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/24px-Brahmi_k.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"64\" data-file-height=\"64\" /></a> and \"Ya\" <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_y.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi y.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Brahmi_y.svg/12px-Brahmi_y.svg.png\" width=\"12\" height=\"12\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Brahmi_y.svg/18px-Brahmi_y.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Brahmi_y.svg/24px-Brahmi_y.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"64\" data-file-height=\"64\" /></a>. Used in the spelling of the word \"<a href=\"/wiki/Shakyas\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Shakyas\">Shakyamuni</a>\" to designate the <a href=\"/wiki/Buddha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buddha\">Buddha</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Lumbini\" title=\"Lumbini\">Rummindei pillar</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Ashoka\" title=\"Ashoka\">Ashoka</a> (circa 250 BCE).</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Conjunct consonants</b> are a type of letters, used for example in <a href=\"/wiki/Brahmi_script\" title=\"Brahmi script\">Brahmi</a> or modern <a href=\"/wiki/Devanagari\" title=\"Devanagari\">Devanagari</a>, to write <a href=\"/wiki/Consonant_cluster\" title=\"Consonant cluster\">consonant clusters</a> such as <span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\">/pr/</span> or <span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\">/rv/</span>. Although most of the time, letters are formed by using a simple consonant with the inherent value vowel \"a\" (as with \"k\" <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_k.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi k.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/12px-Brahmi_k.svg.png\" width=\"12\" height=\"12\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/18px-Brahmi_k.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/24px-Brahmi_k.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"64\" data-file-height=\"64\" /></a>, pronounced \"ka\" in Brahmi), or by combining a consonant with an vowel in the form of an <a href=\"/wiki/Diacritic\" title=\"Diacritic\">diacritic</a> (as with \"ki\" <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi letter Ki.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg/12px-Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg.png\" width=\"12\" height=\"13\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg/18px-Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg/24px-Brahmi_letter_Ki.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"111\" data-file-height=\"124\" /></a> in Brahmi), the usage of conjunct consonant permits the creation of more sophisticated sounds (as with \"kya\" <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_Kya.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi Kya.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Brahmi_Kya.jpg/12px-Brahmi_Kya.jpg\" width=\"12\" height=\"12\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Brahmi_Kya.jpg/18px-Brahmi_Kya.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Brahmi_Kya.jpg/24px-Brahmi_Kya.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"661\" data-file-height=\"675\" /></a>, formed with the consonants k <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_k.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi k.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/10px-Brahmi_k.svg.png\" width=\"10\" height=\"10\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/15px-Brahmi_k.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Brahmi_k.svg/20px-Brahmi_k.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"64\" data-file-height=\"64\" /></a> and y <a href=\"/wiki/File:Brahmi_y.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Brahmi y.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Brahmi_y.svg/10px-Brahmi_y.svg.png\" width=\"10\" height=\"10\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Brahmi_y.svg/15px-Brahmi_y.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Brahmi_y.svg/20px-Brahmi_y.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"64\" data-file-height=\"64\" /></a> assembled verticaly).<sup id=\"cite_ref-MC_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MC-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Conjuncts are often used with loan words. Native words typically use the basic consonant and native speakers know to suppress the vowel.\n</p><p>In modern Devanagari the components of a conjunct are written left to right when possible (when the first consonant has a vertical stem that can be removed at the right), whereas in Brahmi characters are joined vertically downwards.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MC_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MC-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Some simple examples of conjunct consonants in Devanagari are: \u0924 + \u0935 = \u0924\u094d\u0935 tva, \u0923 + \u0922 = \u0923\u094d\u0922 \u1e47\u1e0dha, \u0938 + \u0925 = \u0938\u094d\u0925 stha, where the vertical stroke of the first letter is simply lost in the combination. Sometimes, conjunct consonants are not clearly derived from the letters making up their components: the conjunct for k\u1e63 is \u0915\u094d\u0937 (\u0915\u094d + \u0937) and for j\u00f1 it is \u091c\u094d\u091e (\u091c\u094d + \u091e). \n</p><p>Conjunct consonants are used in many other scripts as well, usually derived from the Brahmi script.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In <a href=\"/wiki/Balinese\" class=\"mw-disambig\" title=\"Balinese\">Balinese</a>, conjunct consonants are called <i>Haksara Wrehastra</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Conjunct consonant are not limited to Brahmic languages, and can be seen in <a href=\"/wiki/Navajo_language\" title=\"Navajo language\">Navajo</a> for example.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Conjunct_consonant&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-MC-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-MC_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-MC_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Shapiro, Michael C. (1989). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=vvuP8sD1wloC&amp;pg=PA23\"><i>A Primer of Modern Standard Hindi</i></a>. Motilal Banarsidass Publ. p.&#160;23. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9788120805088\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9788120805088\">9788120805088</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+Primer+of+Modern+Standard+Hindi&amp;rft.pages=23&amp;rft.pub=Motilal+Banarsidass+Publ.&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.isbn=9788120805088&amp;rft.aulast=Shapiro&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael+C.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DvvuP8sD1wloC%26pg%3DPA23&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AConjunct+consonant\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Tu\u1e45ga, Sudh\u0101\u1e43\u015bu \u015aekhara (1995). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=lRRYBHQvXdsC&amp;pg=PA163\"><i>Bengali and Other Related Dialects of South Assam</i></a>. Mittal Publications. p.&#160;163. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9788170995883\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9788170995883\">9788170995883</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Bengali+and+Other+Related+Dialects+of+South+Assam&amp;rft.pages=163&amp;rft.pub=Mittal+Publications&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.isbn=9788170995883&amp;rft.aula